SIMPLE: prorogation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prorogation
<hw>Pro`ro*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>prorogatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>prorogation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of counting in duration; prolongation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The act of proroguing; the ending of the session of
Parliament, and postponing of its business, by the command of the
sovereign.</def> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ After an adjournment all things continue as they were at
the adjournment; whereas, after a <xex>prorogation</xex>, bill
introduced and nut passed are as if they had never been begun at
all.</note> <rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prorogue</ent>⟦br⟧
